metadata.name: Refractions #260
metadata.description:
Refractions is a study of frequencies, harmonies and abstract representations of natural phenomena. 

It is an experiment of blending three colors to create integrated textural compositions.


Probabilities;

- 14 compositions with variations.

- 2 background color.

- 19 different base color palette (2 monochrome).

- 2 distinct textures with variations.

-  2 different alpha types; tangential & sinusoidal.

- Different edges.

- Several starting positions and styles (wavy or straight).


Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Reconnaissance #214
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe they‚Äôre recon from another planet‚Äôs civilization ‚Äî one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium ‚ÄúThis is Mars,‚Äù Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands ‚Äî and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for what‚Äôs next.


Choose a resolution (1-6) by adding "&scale=4" to the URL in live view.
Created with p5.js

TENDER x Nat Sarkissian

metadata.name: Omega Point #96
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #492
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Sorted #175
metadata.description:
Lo-Res and Hi_Res pixels colors contract and expand, competing with each other for the sorting space.
Capture taken at 14 seconds.
Lots of possible combinations of colors and oscillation and other competitive and directional effects. 

The sixth work by HicPunks on FX Hash and our last on FXHash Beta
Made using Hydra

metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #116
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Sp√∏gelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.

metadata.name: Subsurface Fractures #126
metadata.description:
This generative token runs a shader that simulates the refraction and dispersion of light as it passes through a procedural crystal with fractures under the surface.

Each token has a unique fracture pattern and several hidden properties that define how the light bounces within the crystal. 

Major styles are defined with features, some styles are rarer than others.

This token is GPU intensive, viewing on desktop is recommended.

Press ‚ÄúP‚Äù to pause rotation.
Press ‚ÄúUP‚Äù or ‚ÄúDOWN‚Äù to increase or decrease the number of simulated rays per pixel, this will have an impact on performance.

metadata.name: Unsolicited abstraction of modern times #120
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?‚Ä®‚Ä®

Inspired by textbooks of the 80s, with elements that remind us of industry, technology, networks and systems, "Unsolicited abstraction of modern times" invites us to question our work to date. Has everything really changed?

metadata.name: Intricate 4x4 #50
metadata.description:
'Intricated 4x4' was one of the projects that took me the longest to develop. With each WIP, I realized that I could improve some detail, some feature looking for more pleasant, democratic and varied aesthetic results.

This work consists of generating four sets of particles (ellipses or squares) that appear in the four corners of the screen, respecting the predefined margin limits. These sets move towards the center following an attenuated decrease in size thanks to the combination of logarithm and mapping of frameCount and the size variable. This simple trick ensures smoother and less aggressive movements, bringing the observer a sense of tranquility. 

Combining the use of different palettes with some movement conditionals - functions back() and go() - and a charming touch of shading and depth, 'Intricated 4x4' can be considered one of my favorite 
works and I hope it will be for you, after the mint.

Palletes carefully chosen =)

_______________________________
Variability of editions is ensured by:
* 8 background colors
* 13 palettes x 4 colors = 52 colors picked one by one with a lot of care
* possibility to have a fantastic BW version (rarity: 5%)
* possibility to repeat the same palette for both sets (rarity: 8%)
* possibility to have squares intead of circles (rarity: 25%)
* a wide range of Shapes number
* a well thought number of frames, proportional to the total frameCount to make things 'softer'

_______________________________
Interactive instructions:
* Press [S] to save your .png file
* Press [P] to play/pause your animation anytime you like (this increase exponentially your possibilities, right!?)

_______________________________
Creator: Kukuti
May 2022
License: NFT 2.0

metadata.name: Mur #328
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.
